Data Science Challenge Submission - Phillip Kim¶

Purpose:¶

The purpose of this notebook is to provide a solution for The Iconic's Data Science Challenge.

In this notebook, all four stage tasks will be attempted. The fourth stage task of delivering a reproducible report will be this Jupyter Notebook itself.

Challenge Tasks:¶

Taken from https://github.com/theiconic/datascientist/blob/master/README.md

Stage 1 : Write SQL queries to answer the following questions:

Note: At this stage it is ok to ignore the underlying errors in the data

  1. What was the total revenue to the nearest dollar for customers who have paid by credit card?
  2. What percentage of customers who have purchased female items have paid by credit card?
  3. What was the average revenue for customers who used either iOS, Android or Desktop?
  4. We want to run an email campaign promoting a new mens luxury brand. Can you provide a list of customers we should send to?

Stage 2 : CLEAN - Unhash the data (test_data.zip) using the secret key provided by us, extract it, most importantly clean it and put it in a form you can use - all programatically of course. We have also "intentionally" corrupted two columns in this file - two columns that might look correct but are not correct. They need "some correction" to be useful.

Stage 3 : BUILD - Build a deep learning model (preferably) or any other model that suitably answers this question and predict the inferred gender using the features provided and deriving more featueres at your end. Remember, there is no gender flag, so you are flying blind here.

Stage 4 : DELIVER - Package all your process, findings and code into a reproducible document that can be understood by a business user. A repo of the code branch would be a great thing to have! This reproducible report* must answer the following questions:

  1. How did you clean the data and what was wrong with it? Close to 90% of a Data Scientist's job is in cleaning data
  2. What are the features you used as-is and which one did you engineer using the given ones? What do they mean in the real world?
  3. What does the output look like - how close is the accuracy of the prediction in light of data with labelled flags?
  4. What other features and variables can you think of, that can make this process more robust? Can you make a recommendation of top 5 features you'd seek to find apart from the ones given here
  5. Summarize your findings in an executive summary

</font>

Executive Summary:¶

This section will summarise the exercise and list any findings.

Stage 1 - SQL¶

The SQL queries to answer the questions were executed through the use of sqlite3 Python library.
This method was chosen as to minimise the number of different technology/tool used for this exercise hence even making the queries reproducible.
Effort was taken to make the output easier to read by the use of Pretty Printer Python library and print function formatting.
In practice, it is recommeded to use full-fledged SQL editors for day-to-day querying from a relational database.

Findings¶

  • A sign of potential data duplication was found while running the queries
  • An assumption was made in regards to getting the list of customer to target for the men's luxury brand marketing campaign.
  • The men's luxury brand marketing campaign would be targeting 60% of the total customers in the given dataset

Stage 2 - CLEAN¶

The data duplication was confirmed and then removed upfront before the following cleaning.

Findings¶

  • There were two additional columns not documented in the data definition provided in the README.md file, coupon_discount_applied and redpen_discount_used

Visualisation was applied to the two columns and then assumptions were made in regards the meaning of the two columns.
The data in the two columns were cleaned according to the assumption.

Question raised:
Is "redpen/red pen discount" an industry or The Iconic specific terminology?

Stage 3 - BUILD¶

The data provided did not contain a gender column hence it was not labelled.
An assummption was made and logic was applied to the data to create the inferred gender column (0 being female and 1 being male).
A binary classification model using Keras on top of Tensorflow was created to predict the gender of the customer.

Assumptions:

  1. A customer is likely to purchase a product for themselves.
    That is, a male customer is likely purchase more male product than female products and vice versa.
  2. The women's fashion market is larger than men's so this will be reflected in the number of female customers versus male customers.

Added two mean-based features relating to purchase order conversion:

  • Average cancel on orders
  • Average return on orders

A correlation matrix/heatmap was used to chose the features to use with the derived features.
A cut-off correlation value was chosen and many columns were dropped.
The final dataset to be used in the modelling had a total of 16 features.
A train test data split of 4:1 ratio was applied.

Keras Sequential model with 2 hidden layers were used.
The model takes less than 2.5 minutes to train on a CPU only AWS EC2 instance type t3.medium
Several Scikit Learn functions were used to evaluate the model.
The uneven data distribution was also considered when evaluating the model.
In summary, the model predicated with 99% accuracy with the data set provided.

Findings¶

  • The inferred gender showed there was a ratio of 3.4 : 1, female : male in the given dataset
  • Visualising the two mean-based derived features revealed outliers which could be an indication for data quality issues upstream.
    For analysis purposes this may not be an issue but it may be an issue for existing and future customer/business services implemented with the data.
    It is recommeded to fix the problem at the source if possible.
  • The visualisation revealed the existence of low value customers with near 100% cancellation or return rate on orders.
  • Recommendation is to test the trained model on a bigger dataset.

Other features/recommendations:¶

  1. The inferred gender feature can be implemented better in practice so that the data is closer to the ground truth.
    For example, run a campaign to entice customers to fill in the gender details and then cross checking their inputs using another dataset/database such as sociali media profiles.
  2. The Iconic's customers can be profiled into different categories by combining business logic and data insight.
    A clustering exercise can be helpful for this exercise hence the data science team will play a major role in deriving the customer profiles.
    Once profiled, this data can be added back into the dataset to become a useful feature.
  3. Customer's spending pattern will vary depending on the season.
    That is, holiday periods, special event days such as mother's day etc.
    Hence, features containing this calendar type of data can be useful.
  4. Location data from mobile apps and delivery addresses can be useful for variety of use cases.
    For example, customers with The Iconic mobile apps attending a concert of a celebrity singer.
    Assuming this singer has a fashion line, exclusive promotion alerts can be sent to the customers shortly after the concert
    There are various challenges of monetising data in this manner but many companies are already using customer's data in this manner.
  5. Big data and near-realtime streaming technology has matured in the past few years and it's at a level where is is being used in production across various industries.
    The Iconic can adapt this technology if it hasn't already and tackle granular and high velocity data such as website click stream data.
    The direct business benefit of this is near-realtime service in increasing sales revenue.

Stage 4 - DELIVER¶

Firstly, The Iconic's data scientist challenge repository was cloned to my own GitHub account.
Then this notebook file was added and the repository was made public so that it can be accessed by relevant people.

GitHub:

In [16]:
# Bring it all together to work out the percentage
# Rounding result to 2 decimal places for readability.
cur.execute("""
SELECT
ROUND((SELECT COUNT(1) FROM customers WHERE female_items > 0 AND cc_payments = 1)
/
CAST((SELECT COUNT(1) FROM customers) AS REAL)
* 100, 2)
""")
results = cur.fetchall()
print("%.2f%%" % (results[0][0]))

48.81%

3. What was the average revenue for customers who used either iOS, Android or Desktop?¶

In [17]:
# Other queries which might help to understand revenue
# SELECT MIN(revenue) FROM customers WHERE ios_orders > 0 OR android_orders > 0 OR desktop_orders > 0;
# SELECT MAX(revenue) FROM customers WHERE ios_orders > 0 OR android_orders > 0 OR desktop_orders > 0;
# SELECT AVG(revenue) FROM customers WHERE ios_orders > 0 OR android_orders > 0 OR desktop_orders > 0;

# Rounding result to nearest cent
cur.execute("SELECT ROUND(AVG(revenue), 2) FROM customers WHERE ios_orders > 0 OR android_orders > 0 OR desktop_orders > 0")
results = cur.fetchall()
print("$%.2f" % (results[0][0]))

$1484.89

4. We want to run an email campaign promoting a new mens luxury brand. Can you provide a list of customers we should send to?¶

Assumption:
The logic chosen for the target customer subset is based on whether you have purchased any male/men related products.
Also, including customers who has purchased unisex products.

In [18]:
# Including customers who purchased unisex items as they have potential to purchase 
# SELECT DISTINCT customer_id FROM customers WHERE
# male_items > 0 OR
# mapp_items > 0 OR
# macc_items > 0 OR
# mftw_items > 0 OR
# mspt_items > 0 OR
# unisex_items > 0
cur.execute("""
SELECT DISTINCT customer_id FROM customers WHERE
male_items > 0 OR
mapp_items > 0 OR
macc_items > 0 OR
mftw_items > 0 OR
mspt_items > 0 OR
unisex_items > 0
""")
results = cur.fetchall()
for customer in results:
    print(customer[0])

print("Number of customers to target for campaign: %d" % (len(results)))

Note:
There are 43 columns in the data whereas the data definition according to the README.md file has 41 columns.
The two new columns are coupon_discount_applied and redpen_discount_used.

Assumptions:
Assuming "redpen/red pen discount" is the discount applied to provide the red coloured sale price of items as seen in The Iconic's online shop.

Assuming coupon_discount_applied should be the number of times a discount coupon was applied in the transaction.
Hence the data type should be integer instead of float.

Assuming redpen_discount_used should be the number of times a red pen discount was used.
Hence the data type should be integer instead of float.

Questions:
Is "redpen/red pen discount" an industry or The Iconic specific terminology?

The NaN/NULL values were zeroes but was changed along the data pipeline.

This assumption should not be made in real world world scenarios especially since the records with NaN/NULL values are 22% of the dataset.

Assumption:¶

  1. A customer is likely to purchase a product for themselves.
    That is, a male customer is likely purchase more male product than female products and vice versa.
    This assumption will be used to label the data 0 being female customer and 1 being male customer.
  1. The women's fashion market is larger than men's so this will be reflected in the number of female customers versus male customers.
    We should keep this distribution in mind later when evalulating the model.
In [43]:

df_assumption['male_sum'] = df_X['male_items'] + df_X['mapp_items'] + df_X['mftw_items'] + df_X['macc_items'] + df_X['mspt_items']

                    'returns',
                    'msite_orders',
                    'shipping_addresses',
                    'orders'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Note:
Please note, the above shows the features used for modelling.

Inferred:

  • gender_inferred - inferred gender of the customer using a logic derived from understanding the data, intuition and common sense

Derived:

  • female_sum - total number of women/female related products purchased per customer
  • male_sum - total number of men/male related products purchased per customer
  • avg_cancels_on_orders - average of cancelled orders ( a value between 0 and 1 )
    The customer may not be a valuable customer for The Iconic due to high percentage of cancellations against their orders.
    A potential scenario could be the customer finding a cheaper price on the same product from a competitor's website hence cancelling the earlier purchase from The Iconic.
  • avg_returns_on_orders - average of returned orders ( a value between 0 and 1 )
    Similar to above in regards to high percentage of returned orders.
    A potential scenario could be the customer incorrectly ordering the size/fit.

Used as is:

  • devices
  • male_items
  • female_items
  • mapp_items
  • wapp_items
  • mftw_items
  • wftw_items
  • macc_items
  • wacc_items
  • mspt_items
  • wspt_items

Splitting Data into Train and Test Sets¶

In [59]:
# Specify the data 
X = df_assumption.iloc[:,0:15]

# Specify the target labels and flatten the array
y = df_assumption['gender_inferred']

# Split the data up in train and test sets into 75:25 split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

Standardise the data¶

Standardization is a way to deal with values that lie far apart.

In [60]:
# Define the scaler 
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)

# Scale the train set
X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)

# Scale the test set
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

Build a Keras Model¶

Keras is a high-level neural networks API, written in Python and capable of running on top of TensorFlow, CNTK, or Theano.

  • Using Sequential model type which is a linear stack of layers
  • Using Rectified Linear Unit(ReLU) as the activation function
  • Using two hidden layers
  • Using Sigmoid function(results in 's' shaped curve)
In [61]:
# Initialize the model constructor
model = Sequential()

# Add an input layer matching the shape of the data prepared
model.add(Dense(15, activation='relu', input_shape=(15,)))

# Add two hidden layers
model.add(Dense(12, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))

# Add an output layer
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Using ADAM optimiser

              optimizer='adam',

Out[68]:
array([[8564,    5],
       [   4, 2935]])

Note:

Please interpret the above results as the following:

$\left[ \begin{array}{conf_matrix} Number of correct predictions at female gender(fn), & Number of incorrect predictions at female gender(tn) \\ Number of incorrect predictions at male gender(tp), & Number of correct predictions at female gender(fp) \\ \end{array} \right]$

Therefore, the above results are excellent
